Client wearing #bespoke #threepiecetweed #suit featured in what looks like a pretty big ad campaign here in nyc. We made this suit in 2 weeks flat with of course very few fittings (usually I say 3-4 months for a new client). This was made a few years ago and I still talk about it now, those 2 weeks I did some of my most creative work of my career to make this deadline. Andy Warhol said business is the highest art form I don’t know about that, but despite an art education filled with oil painting, drawing, typography, printmaking etc, for me personally my most creative work has been in business.

Tailoring has always had a diverse workforce which is why as a trade it has its own language. Expressions and words like “french turnup” a “pig” a “kill” a “guardsman cuff” or a “square back” may leave many casual observers scratching their heads. When language fails though there is always functional visual communication be that a photograph or a drawing on a scrap of paper. #bespoketailoring #frontofhouse

Still receiving cloth books for the Store front in Beacon. All of the cloths I use are bought directly from the source and are authentic, no jobbers, no grey market and perish the thought no fakes. I do this for several reasons, I have to trust the cloth. Buying grey market Loro Piana from a market or jobber, I don’t know where it’s from, I don’t know if it’s genuine or if it’s a sample that that was rejected or if it was even stolen, it may have that selvedge on the end but in a world of “super fakes” such as Rolex’s and Louis Vuitton’s you don’t think that bargain cloth could be copied? Next I just don’t have the time to trawl the garment district, even my assistant doesn’t, a good tailor is always busy. Finally it’s piece of mind for myself and the customer. If that fabric fails in some way I can return the cloth or even the garment we have made to the vendor and receive refunds or be compensated. You may think about where your coffee comes from, it’s also good to think about where your cloth comes from as well. #savilerow #hollandandsherry #loropiana #fabricsourcing #ethicalfashion #bespoketailoring in #beaconnewyork and #unionsquarenewyork #slowfashion

I’m never asked what this brass object is that I have next to my chair. Sometimes I play with it in my hands when talking. It looks and feels very dangerous, it’s weighty and sharp and has a nice smooth surface to the touch. It’s not actually some kind of shiv it’s actually a #bauhaus letter opener from 1920s Germany that just feels nice in the hand. Next to it is usually a #alexandervonfursteberg #neon coaster and a couple of replica #isolinearchips in a plexiglass base.
